<TITLE> WHO news conference in Haiti </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 HAITI, Jan 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--- Mirta Rose, Director of the World Health Organization's Pan American Health Organization, said there had been no sign so far of a feared outbreak of contagious diseases among survivors camped out in about 300 makeshift shelters across Port-au-Prince, Hait The World Health Organization's Mirta Rose said on Sunday that the health situation in Haiti was not as bad as could have been expected but that the building of temporary homes by people who have lost everything in the devastating earthquake could cause health problems. Rose, Director of the WHO's Pan American Health Organization, said the good weather helped minimize the risk of the spread of communicable diseases after the quake. "The reporting and surveillance that has been established with the ministry is not showing major problems. But as I mentioned, the people have been establishing temporary settlements and that will be a risky area," she said. "First of all you know the usual things like diarrheal diseases because of the conditions of overcrowding and environmental conditions. Also because we are distributing food and people are not preparing their own meals and so on so there is a massive handling of food so most of the problems are diarrheal diseases in the first moment and all the respiratory transmitted diseases because of the over crowding of people. We are fortunate also that we are living with very good weather," she ad
